actions.comment:
Thanks for the detailed benchmarks and screenshots — very helpful for diagnosis.

The root cause is that `SKCanvasView` in Blazor uses a CPU raster backend. Every frame, Skia does all image scaling in software (per-pixel sampling in WASM), then transfers the full pixel buffer to the HTML canvas via `putImageData`. With GPU-backed `SKGLView`, the same scaling is hardware-accelerated, which is why it handles this fine.

Here's a workaround you can use while we investigate: pre-scale the image once at load time instead of scaling on every frame.

```csharp
// Once at load time — pre-scale to target display size
var targetWidth = 1600;
var targetHeight = 1600;
using var scaledSurface = SKSurface.Create(new SKImageInfo(targetWidth, targetHeight));
if (scaledSurface == null)
    return; // native allocation failed
scaledSurface.Canvas.DrawImage(originalImage,
    new SKRect(0, 0, targetWidth, targetHeight),
    SKSamplingOptions.Default);
var preScaledImage = scaledSurface.Snapshot();
// Cache preScaledImage — dispose when target size changes or on component disposal

// Per frame in OnPaintSurface — draw at 1:1
canvas.DrawImage(preScaledImage, 0, 0);
```

If the target size changes, regenerate the pre-scaled image (and dispose the old one). This avoids per-frame CPU scaling entirely.

You also mentioned issues with `SKGLView` and `DrawLine` calls. Would you be able to file a separate issue for that? Fixing the GL path may be the better long-term solution for image-heavy rendering in Blazor.
